      • getKbObject

        Object getKbObject(String cycLOrId)
            throws KbTypeException,
                   CreateException
        Returns a KbObject which is the best representation for a given String, so long as it doesn't need to be created in the KB. This method is useful in cases where you don't necessarily know what kind of input you will receive, such as when parsing user input. It will attempt to return a KbObject according to these basic rules:
        1. If the string is an ID, return the KbTerm or Assertion associated with that ID.
        2. If the string appears to be a CycL variable, return a Variable.
        3. If the string appears to be a CycL keyword, return a Symbol.
        4. If the string appears to be a CycL sentence, return a Sentence.
        5. If the string appears to be a denotational term, return a KbTerm.

        This differs from #apiObject(String) in that this will throw an exception if given something that is a valid object for the API, but it not a KbObject (e.g. strings and numbers). If you have no idea what kind of object the string represents, it's generally safer to use #apiObject(String).

        When returning a KbTerm or Assertion, this method will always attempt to return an instance of the most specific subclass possible. For example, "#$WeatherQuantity" will be returned as an instance of FirstOrderCollection.

        This method attempts to follow a least-common-denominator principle of least surprise, but do be aware that some strings may have multiple possible representations as KbObjects. For example, this method will return a Variable for "?X", but that string could also be represented as a KbIndividual; if you want "?X" as a KbIndividual, you could accomplish this via a call to KbTerm.get(String) or KbIndividual.get(String). Similarly, almost any string can be a symbol, but the most common type of symbols are keywords, which are prefixed with ":". This method would return a symbol for the string ":SYMBOL", but if you wanted a (non-keyword) symbol for the (un-prefixed) string "SYMBOL", you would need to request it from Symbol.get(String).

        Parameters:
        cycLOrId -
        Returns:
        a KbObject which is the best representation for the given string
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException

      • getApiObject

        Object getApiObject(Object cycLOrId)
             throws KbTypeException,
                    CreateException
        Returns a Object which is the best representation for a given Object (generally a String), so long as it doesn't need to be created in the KB. In general, the version of this that takes a String should be used by application developers. This method will also convert a few other types of objects that are generally only used inside the API, and which are not part of the public API. Typically, this will return KbObjects, but it is typed to return Object, because a number of other classes can be used in CycL. Particularly salient examples of this include Strings and Numbers. This method is useful in cases where you don't necessarily know what kind of input you will receive, such as when parsing user input. It will attempt to return a KbObject according to these basic rules:
        1. If the string is an ID, return the KbTerm, Assertion, String, or Number associated with that ID.
        2. If the string appears to be a CycL variable, return a Variable.
        3. If the string appears to be a CycL keyword, return a Symbol.
        4. If the string appears to be a CycL sentence, return a Sentence.
        5. If the string appears to be a denotational term, return a KbTerm.
        6. If the string is a quoted string, return a String.
        7. If the string is a number, return a Number.

        This differs from #kbObject(String) in that this allows IDs for Strings and Numbers to be used, in addition to IDs for KbObjects. If you have know that your ID is for a KbObject, you can use #kbObject(String) to get a tighter return type.

        When returning a KbTerm or Assertion, this method will always attempt to return an instance of the most specific subclass possible. For example, "#$WeatherQuantity" will be returned as an instance of FirstOrderCollection.

        This method attempts to follow a least-common-denominator principle of least surprise, but do be aware that some strings may have multiple possible representations as KbObjects. For example, this method will return a Variable for "?X", but that string could also be represented as a KbIndividual; if you want "?X" as a KbIndividual, you could accomplish this via a call to KbTerm.get(String) or KbIndividual.get(String). Similarly, almost any string can be a symbol, but the most common type of symbols are keywords, which are prefixed with ":". This method would return a symbol for the string ":SYMBOL", but if you wanted a (non-keyword) symbol for the (un-prefixed) string "SYMBOL", you would need to request it from Symbol.get(String).

        Parameters:
        cycLOrId -
        Returns:
        an Object (possibly a KbObject) which is the best representation for the given input
        Throws:
        KbTypeException
        CreateException

      • getApiObjectDwim

        Object getApiObjectDwim(String cycLOrId)
                 throws KbTypeException,
                        CreateException
        Returns a Object which is the best representation for a given String, so long as it doesn't need to be created in the KB. Generally, this will return KbObjects, but it is typed to return Object, because a number of other classes can be used in CycL. Particularly salient examples of this include Strings and Numbers. This method is useful in cases where you don't necessarily know what kind of input you will receive, such as when parsing user input. It will attempt to return a KbObject according to these basic rules:
        1. If the string is an ID, return the KbTerm, Assertion, String, or Number associated with that ID.
        2. If the string is starts and ends with { and }, return a Set containing the elements between the brackets.
        3. If the string is starts and ends with [ and ], return a List containing the elements between the brackets.
        4. If the string appears to be a CycL variable, return a Variable.
        5. If the string appears to be a CycL keyword, return a Symbol.
        6. If the string appears to be a CycL sentence, return a Sentence.
        7. If the string appears to be a denotational term, return a KbTerm.
        8. If the string is a quoted string, return a String.
        9. If the string is a number, return a Number.

        This differs from #kbObject(String) in that this allows IDs for Strings and Numbers to be used, in addition to IDs for KbObjects. If you have know that your ID is for a KbObject, you can use #kbObject(String) to get a tighter return type.

        When returning a KbTerm or Assertion, this method will always attempt to return an instance of the most specific subclass possible. For example, "#$WeatherQuantity" will be returned as an instance of FirstOrderCollection.

        This method attempts to follow a least-common-denominator principle of least surprise, but do be aware that some strings may have multiple possible representations as KbObjects. For example, this method will return a Variable for "?X", but that string could also be represented as a KbIndividual; if you want "?X" as a KbIndividual, you could accomplish this via a call to KbTerm.get(String) or KbIndividual.get(String). Similarly, almost any string can be a symbol, but the most common type of symbols are keywords, which are prefixed with ":". This method would return a symbol for the string ":SYMBOL", but if you wanted a (non-keyword) symbol for the (un-prefixed) string "SYMBOL", you would need to request it from Symbol.get(String).

        Returns:
        an Object (possibly a KbObject) which is the best representation for the given input

      • clearCache

        void clearCache()
        Clears all caches relating KbObjects to objects on the Cyc server. In most applications, this will not be needed. However, it can be helpful in applications where the KB is modified externally. For example, if a Cyc term is deleted and then recreated with the same name by some external process, the KB API will still have the id information from the old constant, and will retrieve the new constant. A call to clearCache will clear the cache and allow the KB API to successfully retrieve the newly created constant.
